solutions.content:
**Intuition:**
The idea is to generate trees in inorder fashion , making each number in the range[1.n] as the root one by one and recursively obtaining its left and right subtrees ensuring that BST properties doesnt gets violated.
If the Root Value is i
* Left subtree will contain values in range[start,i-1]
* right subrees will contain valyes in range[i+1,end]

for a particular root value 'i' there are many left and right subtrees possible , so generate all of them and combine all of them and appending to our final result vector of all BSTs.

**Base Case:**
There are two base cases:
*  If start exceeds end; start>end, there is no tree possible, so instead of returning empty list (which will cause unexpected loop termination in the parent recursive call) , we will append null to the result list and return result.
*  if start=end, there is only one number in range i.e. start, so only one Tree possible rooted at start and left and right subtree as null, so, make this tree and add to result list and return.

Here is my code:
```

class Solution {
public:
    vector<TreeNode*> generateTrees(int n) {
        return helper(1,n);//To generate all the BST possible in range(1,n) 
    }
    vector<TreeNode*> helper(int start, int end){
        vector<TreeNode*> allTrees;//vector to store all bsts
        if(start>end)//base case
        {
            allTrees.push_back(NULL); //No Tree is possible if start>end so push none and return
            return allTrees;
        }
        if(start==end) // Base case 2 
        {
            TreeNode* root=new TreeNode(start); // if there is only 1 number in range i.e. start=end then make th
                                                // only number as root node and return
            allTrees.push_back(root);
            return allTrees;

        }
        // making all numbers from start to end as root one by one and generating their left and right subtrees according to BST rules
        for(int CurRootVal=start;CurRootVal<=end;CurRootVal++)
        {
        vector<TreeNode*>allLeftSubtrees=helper(start,CurRootVal-1); // generated Leftsubtrees contains values in range[start,currootvalue-1]
            vector<TreeNode*>allRightSubtrees=helper(CurRootVal+1,end); //generated rightsubtrees contains values in range[currootvalue+1,end]
            for(auto leftsubtree : allLeftSubtrees) // traversing each of the left subtrees generated
            {
                for(auto rightsubtree : allRightSubtrees) // for each left subtree, all the right subtrees generated are traversed and combined as below 
                {
                    TreeNode* curRoot=new TreeNode(CurRootVal); // making root node of value curRootVal
                    curRoot->left=leftsubtree; // adding leftsubtree to the left child of current root
                    curRoot->right=rightsubtree;// adding right subtree to the right child of current root
                    allTrees.push_back(curRoot);// appending the tree generated to the result alltrees
                }
            }

        }
        return allTrees;

    }
};
```

