# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
By using start and end variables to generate all the trees.

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Now let's look how our helper function will work!

1. As there will be trees with root as 1, 2, 3...n. Iterate through all values from start to end to construct tree rooted at i and construct its left and right subtree recursively.
2. We know that in Binary Search Tree all nodes in left subtree are smaller than root and in right subtree are larger than root. So for start = 1 and end = n, if we have ith number as root, all numbers from 1 to i-1 will be in left subtree and i+1 to n will be in right subtree.
Therefore, we will build the tree recursively for left and right subtrees rooted at i as leftSubTree = bst(start, i-1) and rightSubtree = bst(i + 1, end)
So, till what moment we will recursively find the left and right subtrees?? Answer is until start < end!!
So when start > end, add NULL to the list and return
This will be our base case!
3. Now, we have leftSubtree and rightSubtree for node with root i. The last thing we need to do is connect leftSubTree and rightSubTree with root and add this tree(rooted at i) to the ans list!
📌 Here, we can have multiple left and right subtrees. So we need to loop through all left and right subtrees and connect every left subTree to right subTree and to current root(i) one by one.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
-> catalan Number(O(4^n/n^1.5)) * O(n) for generating the trees
-> O(4^n/n^0.5).

- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
-> recursion stack space.

# Code
```
/**
 * Definition for a binary tree node.
 * struct TreeNode {
 *     int val;
 *     TreeNode *left;
 *     TreeNode *right;
 *     TreeNode() : val(0), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
 *     TreeNode(int x) : val(x), left(nullptr), right(nullptr) {}
 *     TreeNode(int x, TreeNode *left, TreeNode *right) : val(x), left(left), right(right) {}
 * };
 */
class Solution {
public:
    vector<TreeNode*> generate(int i, int j) {
        vector<TreeNode*> res;
        if(i > j) {
            res.push_back(NULL);
            return res;
        }
        for(int ind = i;ind <= j;ind++) {
            vector<TreeNode*> left = generate(i, ind-1);
            vector<TreeNode*> right = generate(ind+1, j);
            for(auto l: left) {
                for(auto r: right) {
                    TreeNode* root = new TreeNode(ind, l, r);
                    res.push_back(root);
                }
            }
        }
        return res;
    }
    vector<TreeNode*> generateTrees(int n) {
        return generate(1, n);
    }
};
```

