solutions.content:
For some reason, there is a lack of well documented solution using TreeSet for Java developers in the discussion. Official LC solution uses C++ multiset and iteration there gets easier because of pointers, which is hard to achieve using iterators in Java (considering there is no *peek* functionality in Java iterators).

The following code uses two pointer approach, and becomes a bit long because of using a custom comparator. The idea here is: instead of an iterator, we store both the number and its location in data stream in the TreeSet. This lets us handle cases where identical values are entered in the stream, and closely follows the height balanced trees approach presented in LC solution.

This is an important technique to grasp in case interviewer asks for alternative solutions to the more popular Priority Queue approach.

Time complexity for add is O(log(n)) to account for the time to `add` and search (`lower` and `upper` methods of TreeSet).
Space complexity is O(n) since we are storing all elements of the stream here

```
class MedianFinder {
    TreeSet<int[]> data;
    Comparator<int[]> customComparator;
    int[] lower, upper;
    int index;
    /** initialize your data structure here. */
    public MedianFinder() {
        // Comparator compares first by value of the integer, then by location in stream
        customComparator = ((int[] a, int[] b) -> {
            if (a[0] != b[0]) {
                return Integer.compare(a[0], b[0]);
            }
            else {
                return Integer.compare(a[1], b[1]);
            }
        });
        data = new TreeSet<>(customComparator);
        lower = null;
        upper = null;
        index = 0;
    }

    public void addNum(int num) {
        int[] curr = new int[] {num, index++};
        data.add(curr);
        if (data.size() == 1) {
            // First addition to the stream
            lower = data.first();
            upper = data.first();
        }
        else if (customComparator.compare(lower, upper) == 0) {
            // last time it was odd, now it is even
            if (customComparator.compare(curr, lower) < 0) {
                // num is less than the left median
                // Median has shifted one place left
                upper = lower;
                lower = data.lower(lower);
            }
            else {
                // num is greater than or eaual to the right median
                // Median has shifted one place right
                lower = upper;
                upper = data.higher(upper);
            }
        }
        else {
            // last time it was even, this time it is odd
            // Three cases
            if (customComparator.compare(curr, lower) < 0) {
                // Case 1: new number inserted to the left of lower
                // lower median is the current median in that case
                upper = lower;
            }
            else  if (customComparator.compare(curr, upper) > 0) {
                // Case 2: new number inserted to the right of upper
                // upper median is the current median in that case
                lower = upper;
            }
            else{
                // Case 3: Either num is equal to one or both of upper, lower, or lies in between
                // in that case, num IS our median
                lower = curr;
                upper = curr;
            }
        }

    }

    public double findMedian() {
        if (lower == null) {
            // Safety check
            return 0.0;
        }
        // This function is trivial since we are already tracking two pointers
        return ((double)lower[0] + upper[0])/2;
    }
}
```

Note: inspired by https://leetcode.com/problems/find-median-from-data-stream/discuss/439595/Java-TreeSet-Solution-beats-93, but wanted to add more commented and clean code.

