The idea is to maintain a TreeMap<Number, Count> and a mid value along with its relative index to it's count.
Each time a number is added the relative index is incremented or decremented.

For example if we have numbers 10, 10, 10, 15, **15**, 15, 20, 20, 20
The map contains:
10: 3
15: 3
20: 3
mid value is 15 and the relative index is 1 (pointing to the second 15)

When another 20 is added it becomes
map:
10: 3
15: 3
20: 4
mid value is still 15 and the relative index is 2 (pointing to the third 15)

Another 20:
10: 3
15: 3
20: 5
mid value is still 20 and the relative index is 0 (pointing to the first 20)

```
class MedianFinder {

    private final TreeMap<Integer, Integer> tree = new TreeMap<>();
    private int totalCount;

    private int midValue;
    private int midIndex;

    /** initialize your data structure here. */
    public MedianFinder() {
    }

    public void addNum(int num) {
        tree.put(num, tree.getOrDefault(num, 0) + 1);
        totalCount++;

        if (totalCount == 1) {
            midValue = num;
            midIndex = 0;
        } else {
            if (num >= midValue) {
                midIndex++;
                if (midIndex / 2 >= tree.get(midValue)) {
                    midValue = tree.higherKey(midValue);
                    midIndex = 0;
                }
            } else {
                midIndex--;
                if (midIndex < 0) {
                    midValue = tree.lowerKey(midValue);
                    midIndex = tree.get(midValue) * 2 - 1;
                }
            }
        }
    }

    public double findMedian() {
        if (totalCount % 2 == 0 && (midIndex + 1) / 2 >= tree.get(midValue)) {
            int nextMidValue = tree.higherKey(midValue);
            return (midValue + nextMidValue) / 2d;
        } else {
            return midValue;
        }
    }
}
```

