**Using Insertion sort**
```
class MedianFinder {

    ArrayList<Integer> a;
    public MedianFinder() {
        a = new ArrayList<>();
    }

    public void addNum(int num) {
        if(a.size()==0){
            a.add(num);
            return;
        }
        a.add(num);
        int j = a.size()-2;
        while(j >= 0 && a.get(j) > num) {
            a.set(j + 1,a.get(j));
            j--;
        }
        a.set(j + 1,num);
    }

    public double findMedian() {
        if(a.size()%2==0){
            return (a.get(a.size()/2)+a.get((a.size()-1)/2)+0.0)/2;
        } else{
            return a.get(a.size()/2)+0.0;
        }
    }
}
```

**Using Heap**
Approach :
divide the aray in two halfs and store left half in max heap and right half in min heap.
so that when we need to find median the mid element are at the top of max heap or min heap

example  :
when array is even
arr = [2,4,5,6]

max_heap: 2 4
min_heap = 6 5

median is top of max_heap+minheap/2; = (4+5)/2

when array is odd

arr = [2,3,4,5,6]

max_heap: 2 3 4 
min_heap = 6 5

median is top of max_heap = 4

Now this will work when we have sorted array so, we have to insert element in heap such that the all element in max heap is less than all element in min heap .

**0.0 in code is added to typecast from int to double**
