# Follow up
1. Maintain an array of size `101` such that for each number `i` in `[0,100]` we know the count of numbers smaller than or equal to `i`. And, we binary search for median; median has half the numbers smaller than or equal to it. So, we can binary search in that array for finding median - since it'll be in non-decreasing order.

```
class MedianFinder {
    private int[] se = new int[101];

    public MedianFinder() {
    }

    public void addNum(int num) {
        for (int i = num; i < se.length; i++) {
              se[i]++;
        }
    }

    public double findMedian() {
        int n = se[100];
        int middle = (n + 1) / 2;
        double ans = smallestEqualOrGreater(middle);
        if (n % 2 == 0) {
            ans += smallestEqualOrGreater(middle + 1);
            ans /= 2;
        }
        return ans;
    }

    private int smallestEqualOrGreater(int key) {
        int lo = 0, hi = se.length - 1;
        int index = -1;
        while (lo <= hi) {
            int mid = (lo + hi) / 2;
            if (se[mid] >= key) {
                index = mid;
                hi = mid - 1;
            } else {
                lo = mid + 1;
            }
        }
        return index;
    }
}
```

2. What changes for the second follow up? Keeping counters for elements smaller than `0` and greater than `100` should suffice. And, we use `se` array only for the purpose; indexes `0` and `102`. Why only counters are enough for numbers outside the range `[0,100]`? Only `1%` of the numbers are outside of that range, so the median will never be outside of the range; so, we need not remember those numbers.

```
class MedianFinder {
    private int[] se = new int[103];

    public MedianFinder() {
    }

    public void addNum(int num) {
	    int start = num + 1;
	    if (num < 0) {
		    start = 0;
		}
		if (num > 100) {
		    start = 102;
		}
        for (int i = start; i < se.length; i++) {
              se[i]++;
        }
    }

    public double findMedian() {
        int n = se[102];
        int middle = (n + 1) / 2;
		// remember, index=0 corresponds to negative numbers
        double ans = smallestEqualOrGreater(middle) - 1;
        if (n % 2 == 0) {
            ans += smallestEqualOrGreater(middle + 1) - 1;
            ans /= 2;
        }
        return ans;
    }

    private int smallestEqualOrGreater(int key) {
        int lo = 0, hi = se.length - 1;
        int index = -1;
        while (lo <= hi) {
            int mid = (lo + hi) / 2;
            if (se[mid] >= key) {
                index = mid;
                hi = mid - 1;
            } else {
                lo = mid + 1;
            }
        }
        return index;
    }
}
